AB  - Most mechanical components used in the transportation industry are subjected to more than one type of stress. This paper makes a short review of previous work in the field of mechanical reliability, then proposes a computerized technique for predicting the reliability of a mechanical component when it is subjected to mean torque and alternating bending stresses. By considering the stress ratio as nonconstant, these stresses form a bivariate distribution. When this bivariate distribution is coupled with a bivariate distribution of strength, the volume of intersection of these two distributions is the probability that the component fails due to the combined mean and alternating stresses. The probability that the component fails due to the alternating stress, QA, and the mean stress QM is computed using a technique already published by one of the authors. The resultant reliability of the component is given by R = 1 - (QA + QM - QAQM). © 1980.
